# CS51 Assignment 2: Algorithms and Simulation

## OVERVIEW


This assignment has two distinct parts in addition to a reflection: Part 1 requires you to apply your knowledge of algorithmic thinking and optimization and Part 2 allows you to demonstrate your modeling and coding skills by writing a numerical simulation. Material relevant for Part 1 will be covered in class during weeks 3-5, while material relevant for Part 2 will be covered in class during weeks 7 and 8. 


You'll notice several "*Optional Challenge*" problems throughout the assignment to challenge yourself. These will only be scored (4 or 5) if they are completed correctly with thorough explanation. If you attempt an optional challenge but do not succeed, you will not be penalized with a low score. Remember that you must include an explanation and interpretation for optional problems to be scored.


*This is an individual assignment. We will be checking for similarities among submissions and will take plagiarism seriously*.

## FORMAT

For optimal formatting, please use [Markdown and Code cells appropriately](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RHoHCt_yWjOu7pGSCgPnLMJqY5H-w8Uf/view?usp=sharing) (more tips in this [Markdown cheatsheet](https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/en/SSGNPV_1.1.3/dsx/markd-jupyter.html)) and ensure ALL components of your work (including written analysis, images, tables, and code) are presented professionally. Anything marked as optional will only be scored if it is completed correctly. *Tip to avoid grammar and spelling errors*: do your writing using a program that is compatible with Grammarly, then copy your work into the notebook.

## HC GUIDELINES

You will be graded on the targeted HCs (#algorithms, #optimization, #modeling, #dataviz, #variables, #selfawareness) as indicated above in square brackets, at the discretion of the professor. "Footnotes" for these targeted HCs are not required. Please refer to the rubrics and your class notes as guidelines for these HCs. The optional challenges will only be given extra HC scores (4s or 5s) for correct and well-explained implementations that demonstrate deep knowledge.


If you believe that you have strong applications of other HCs, such as #estimation or #utility, please call this out. Doing so is an important part of reflecting on your learning. It should be an occasion for #selfawareness and #professionalism. However, since footnotes are not possible in Jupyter notebooks, simply provide the hashtag of the HC and a 1-3 sentence explanation of your application in a Markdown cell. Help the professor understand exactly why this constitutes a strong application. For guidelines on how to integrate HCs in your work and write meaningful footnotes, please see this guide, [Addressing HCs in your work](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1s7yOVOtMIaHQdKLeRmZbq1gRqwJKfezBsfru9Q6PcHw/edit?usp=sharing), particularly section 3. For more samples of effective annotations, refer to the footnotes that go along with each HC example in the Outcome Index, written in square brackets.

## PART 1: OPTIMIZATION

For this section of the assignment, you will select one of the two scenarios below to describe how to optimize. You must complete all sections. [#optimization, potentially relevant: #modeling, #algorithms, #variables, #utility, #constraints]

1. *Scenario 1*: To prevent the spread of an infectious disease, a vaccine needs to be distributed as quickly and efficiently as possible to the 15 cities that have had major outbreaks. How can you optimize the route between the cities? For this scenario, you should select cities that are relevant to the disease that you will choose for PART 2 and include a map of these cities (you may use an existing map or draw your own). 


2. *Scenario 2*: Suppose that a new virus is starting to spread, and many clinics do not have sophisticated diagnostic tools and must be able to determine whether or not a patient has this dangerous virus based solely on easily measured symptoms. You have been collecting information on symptoms (temperature, WBC count, headache severity, and cough severity) and you need to determine which patients have this new disease and which have only a milder illness. Plots that provide an overview of the data are available [here](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1td_jCTzYiOCMPJ8CwVSJU7u-pQ-5R1JW/view?usp=sharing). The data can be accessed at [this link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1smz8OhVkIAbWVKpmkx7liE3bOWLfQch7/view?usp=sharing) (1 = Infected, 0 = Not infected).

#### 1.1 Optimization Problem: 
Choose a scenario from above. Describe the optimization problem for your scenario: what is the objective function? What are the decision variables? Are there any constraints? (<150 words)

In the second scenario where a new virus is spreading and clinics don't have sufficient tools to find out who has the virus. The problem is a classification optimization one because we need to build a classification model. We want to find the best tree that serves as a model and classify the data. The objective function is maximizing the testing accuracy of the model. The decision variables are the order of symptoms in the tree, where to make a branch cut, maximum depth of the tree, minimum sample to leave in a leaf node. The constraints are the variables that cannot be manipulated to reach the objective function which are the available data of the patients, and the number of available symptoms we collected.

#### 1.2 Optimization Technique: 

What process can be used to find the optimal solution in your scenario? Identify and describe an existing algorithm that could be used to complete this process, including the inputs, outputs, and required steps. Name at least one other optimization technique that could be applied in this scenario and justify why you selected the technique you chose. Address whether your algorithm would lead to the global optimum. Hint: Some possible optimization algorithms that could be appropriate for this optimization problem were discussed in class.Optional but encouraged: Draw a flowchart to illustrate the process.  (<200 words)

Classification tree algorithm. This is a supervised learning algorithm (has predefined target variables) that is used to split a sample into two or more homogenous categories. In this scenerio, the independent variables, also the input, are the temperature, WBC count, headache severity and cough severity because they are the given parameters that do not depend on others. The dependent variable is a categorical or boolean data type which classifies the patients into 1 (infected) and 0(not infected). A possible confounding variable is the time in which the data was taken. Maturation effects and regression to the mean might make those that were not previously infected get the virus or vice versa which skews the output of the classification. The first process is growing a tree. A tree is grown based on conditions set on the variables as they are ordered on a decision tree. The first variable is the highest according to a statistical calculation like Gini or Chi test. The tree is grown with a training data set which is typically about 80% of the total data. Because this is a supervised learning where target variables are known, the accuracy of the training data is calculated. The remaining dataset(20% of data), called the testing data is used to test the classification model. The output is the percent accuracy of the training and testing data, which is a numeric continuous variable. The accuracy is gotten by dividing the number of correct classifications by the total, then multiplying by 100%. In this optimization process, our aim is to maximize the testing data accuracy or minimize the error. Another optimization process is the perceptron. I chose decision tree over a perceptron because the data is not linearly separable and it contains more than two variable, which would be difficult for a percepton. Also, the decision trees are efficient both numerical and categorical data types. A decision tree is a greedy algorithm because it tries to categorize dat points locally rather than globally, which sometimes results in overfitting, when the training accuracy is too perfect and testing accuracy is not optimal. 

Decision tree process

* Decide the order of variables in the tree 
* Set conditions for the branches of the tree
* Grow the tree using the training dataset
* Set constraints on the tree
* Test the model with the testing dataset
* Calculate the accuracy of the training and testing data
* Adjust the max_depth until the training accuracy gets to its highest.

# imports packages for dataframe

                                                                            all_classes, train_size=0.7,

# grow a tree!!!
dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=6) #grows a tree with a maximum depth of 6

#### 1.3 Interpretation: 

Describe how the results of the optimization could be interpreted. What are the limitations of these interpretations? (<50 words)

The results would be the accuracy score of both the training and testing sets. The inetrpretation is that X% of data was correctly categorized. A high training accuracy and a low testing accuracy means that the model is not at its global maximum. The most optimum solution is the highest value of the testing accuracy in percentage. The limitation of a decision tree interpretation is overfitting which is a phenomenon where the training set's accuracy is 100% but the tests' accuracy is less than optimal. This is prevented by pruning and setting constraints like maximum depth, and highest sample number.

## PART 2: SIMULATION

The SIR model of the spread of disease is commonly used to help understand how a disease might move through a population. You were introduced to this with the [NetLogo](http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/Virus) agent-based model in NS50 and will review it again in Week 7 of CS51. The following links will help you learn more about the SIR model: 

- An accessible [video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XWXqXzAYe4E) introduction to the SIR model

- A [paper](http://op12no2.me/stuff/tjsir.pdf) that describes the SIR model and its numerical simulation

- A series of [educational lessons](https://www.maa.org/press/periodicals/loci/joma/the-sir-model-for-spread-of-disease-the-differential-equation-model) on the SIR model


For this assignment, you will select one disease of your choice to model. Please choose a disease from [THIS LIST](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1_p_6W8Zh07XFwuQ3EzkT7PEdbtwTzejHbpKm_wBOLas/edit?usp=sharing) to investigate. If you would like to select your own disease to model, you may email your professor with the disease and parameter descriptions for approval. You must select an infectious disease (one that is transmitted from person to person through a viral, bacterial, or parasitic agent), not a genetic or environmental disease.

### 2.1 Numerical Modeling and Simulation

#### 2.1.1 Numerical Modeling: 
Describe the disease you selected to model and explain how you will set up the model of disease dynamics as a set of differential equations. Identify the relevant variables and explain what they mean in the context of your model. Explain how to select appropriate values for the relevant parameters, including the initial values. You're encouraged to use empirical data if possible to justify these values. You may also complete a well-reasoned estimation for any values that are difficult to justify with empirical data. Explain any assumptions of your model. [#modeling, #variables, and potentially #estimation]  (<150 words)

Coronavirus. Coronavirus is a novel virus that was first gotten in Wuhan, China. The modes of transmission are mainly through body contact and air. Common symptoms include respiratory difficulties, fever, cough, and shortness of breath.  
I would set up the model of the virus dynamics using the SIR model.
The independent variable is time  t, which is measured in days.
The dependent variables are:

* S = S(t) the number of susceptible individuals which is the number that is at risk of getting Coronavirus in Wuhan. According to World Health Orgainzation, 80% of those infected in China are between 30-70 years of age (Yale Global, 2020). This puts people within this age group at risk of being infected. By estimate, Wuhan's population is about 8 million while about half of the population is betwen 25 and 65 (Yale Gobal, 2020). 80% of half of 8 million is 3.2 million people and the remaining 20% of other half is 800 thousand, which both sums up to 4 million susceptible people. This number is plausible since the virus has reached every corner in Wuhan and thereby makes almost half of the Wuhan susceptible.
* I = I(t) the number of infected individuals as of March 2020 is 106,211 (Worldometer, 2020)
* R = R(t) is the number of recovered individuals, which includes both recovered and dead from Coronavirus (removed), is 63,813 (Worldometer, 2020).
* N = Number in the popuation which is 4535024

The parameters are:
* The infectous rate ,$\beta$ , which is the rate at which people get infected is 0.50065
* The recovery rate,$\gamma$, which is the rate at which people recover and get removed(die) is 0.0181

Equation
1. $\frac{ds}{dt}=-\beta s(t)i(t)$   The rate of change in susceptible population in Wuhan
2. $\frac{di}{dt}=\beta s(t)i(t)-\gamma i(t)$   The rate of change of infected population
3. $\frac{dr}{dt}=\gamma i(t)$   The rate of change of recovered/dead population

Assumptions
* I assumed that the population is fixed.
* I assumed that the only way a person can leave the susceptible group is by getting infected and the only way a person can leave the infected group is either by recovery or death.
* Finally, I assumed the population mix homogenously and immunity is not inherited.

#### 2.1.2 Numerical Simulation: 

Implement a numerical simulation to derive the implications of your model using Euler's method in Python. Include thorough comments in your code to convey your understanding of the implementation of Euler's method. [#algorithms]

***Optional Super Challenge***: Modify your code to add a layer of real-world complexity, such as:

- Vaccination

- Antibiotic use and/or development of antibiotic resistance

- Variability in population susceptibility (e.g. children and the elderly have different rates of infection compared to young adults).

Be sure to explain what you are doing, and add extra cells in the notebook as needed.

#### 2.1.3 Visualization: 

Create at least one relevant visualization of the disease dynamics. Include a descriptive figure legend. [#dataviz].

# Imports the numpy array module
import numpy as np

t0 = 0 # stores the initial t(time) value 
t_end = 48 #stores the t values after which the code will stop

h = .1 #step size
steps = int((t_end - t0)/h + 1) # finds number of steps with the Euler formula 

t = np.linspace(t0, t_end, steps) # stores t values
S = np.zeros(steps) #  stores S values
I = np.zeros(steps) #  stores I values
R = np.zeros(steps) #  stores R values
N = 4535024  #the total population in the system
b =  0.050065 #the rate of infection of Corona
k = 0.0181   # Corona's rate of recovery

def dSdt(t,S,I):
    # defines the dS/dt and returns the change over time using the SIR formula
    return -b*S*I/N 

def dIdt(t,S,I):
    # dI/dt
    return (b*S/N-k)*I

def dRdt(t,S,I):
    #dR/dt
    return k*I

# sets the initial conditions
S[0] = 4365000 # Worldmeter(2020)
I[0] = 106211 # Worldmeter(2020)
R[0] = 63813 #Worldmeter(2020)

for i in range(steps-1): # runs a loop for the numbe4 of steps it takes
    S[i+1] = S[i] + dSdt(t[i],S[i],I[i])# Adds previous y-value of susceptible to change 
    I[i+1] = I[i] + dIdt(t[i],S[i],I[i])# Adds previous y-value of infected to change
    R[i+1] = R[i] + dRdt(t[i], S[i], I[i]) #Adds previous y-value of recovered to change

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  #imports the visualization package
%matplotlib inline
#sets a fontsize
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 15}) 
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [8,5]
#plots the S,I and R nd labels the legends
plt.plot(t,S,linewidth=2,label='S(t)')
plt.plot(t,I,linewidth=2,label='I(t)')
plt.plot(t,R,linewidth=2,label='R(t)')
plt.xlabel('t (days)')
plt.ylabel('S,  I (people)')
plt.title("Coronavirus simulation using the Euler's method" )
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

#### 2.1.4 SIR Model vs Numerical Simulation: 

What is the relationship between the SIR model differential equations and the numerical simulation you created? You may consider, for example, whether the model and simulation are continuous or discrete. You should also consider what it means to solve the SIR model and how your numerical simulation via Euler's method is helpful for this purpose. [#modeling] (<120 words)

The SIR model differential equation is a set of underlying equations that describes the behavior of the infection system over time to make predictions on pattern of virus behavior while the numerical simulation ouputs the visual result that is readable to humans by running it. In simple terms, we build a model and run a simulation. The differential equation is continuous because model functions based on time that runs without a discrete stop, similar to running water. The numerical simulation is discrete because it is run on time steps, which stops at intervals. Solving an SIR differential equation is getting an algebraic function that consistst of constants and variables. The numerical simulation serves as an alternative when the formula method is not feasible. It provides an alternative approach to solving for functions which are the solution to the differential equation. However, the Euler's method is likely to overestimate convex graphs and underestimate concave graphs because it uses the previous slopes to calculate the next point.

#### 2.1.5 Numerical Results and Interpretation: 

Describe how the results of the numerical simulation can be interpreted, being sure to reference the output in the visualization. What insights can be gained from this simulation? What happened when you ran the model with varying parameter choices? What limitations does this simulation have? Note: To fully interpret the results, you should run the simulation multiple times with varying parameter inputs and observe the behavior of your model. [#modeling] (<120 words)

From the simulation, the number of susceptible sharply decreased the original population of 4 million over time before slowly reducing and reaching an equilibrium close to zero. The infected population increased from 63000 to more than a million, then it decreased sharply and gently till it got to zero, meaning that no one got infected after 50 days. The recovery population was converse to the susceptible as it increased sharply then gently signally that everyone that got Coronavirus recovered after 50 days. When I increased the step size to 1, the graph showed the parameters stretch to infinity without ever intersecting. When I used a very high infection rate, b, the infected population spiked to the peak at the very beginning, then decreased slowly. The Euler's method is prone to overestimatation  and underestimation because it uses the previous slopes to calculate the next point, which is not an approximation of the original slope and it's interpretation is also limited by the inconsideration of immunity, and constriction to only three variables.

###  Agent-Based Modeling and Simulation

#### 2.2.1 Agent-Based Modeling: 

Use the [NetLogo](http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/Virus) model to simulate the spread of your selected disease. To do so, be sure to choose appropriate parameters for your selected disease and justify them. Provide a brief overview of this model, including a description of the algorithm that NetLogo uses for the simulation and the main assumptions involved. [#modeling, #variables] (<150 words)

A Netlogo model is a programmable modelling environment that simulates natural phenomena. Netlogo is an agent based model typically models complex systems which consists of agents that follow simple rules and interact with one another to produce a micro- or macro- level emergence. The Virus Netlogo model consists of parameters such as infectiousness and chance of recovery which can be adjusted based on a specific virus, variables like healthy(green), infected(red) and immune(grey) and also a graph that shows the trend of the disease over time. As an algorithm, the inputs are the infectiousness, duration, and chance recovery which are numeriacal continous data types and number of people and time tick which is numerical discrete. A confounding variable is the immunity number, which would affect the rate of becomming free from the virus. The process is a random interaction amongst heterogenous individuals. The ouput shows the percentage of people that are infected, immune, the number of years passed and a graph showing the trend. The main assumption is that people mix randomly and the virus is transmitted by the interaction between the healthy and infected. I set the infectiousness as 5%, which is almost the same as my SIR model's b= 0.05 and chance recovery as 1%, corresponding to k = 0.01.

#### 2.2.3 Agent-Based Model Interpretation: 

After running the simulation multiple times, describe how the results from the agent-based simulation can be interpreted, being sure to reference the output in the visualization above. What insights can be gained from this simulation? What limitations does this simulation have? [#modeling] (<100 words)

With the parameters from Coronavirus, the number of sick people increased in the first weeks, then decreased after the third week while the healthy population increased due to the infected percentage coming down from 10% to 0%. This simulation provides us with the dynamics of a virus with a low infectiousness and chance of recovery like Coronavirus. According to the simulation, the infected percentage will recover/die after 0.4 of a year (roughly four months), which is when the system stabilizes. The limitation is random interaction between the population, which barely happens in real world because most people mix within a homogenous community. Also, the model doesn't account for difference in infectiousness based on gender or age.

#### 2.2.4 Simulation Comparison: 

Compare and contrast the numerical simulation you wrote in Python with the NetLogo virus simulation. Based on all of the above analysis, what are the biggest differences between these simulations, and which one is a more realistic representation of nature? Why? Be sure to address whether these are stochastic or deterministic simulations and to consider the results. [#modeling] (<100 words)

Both the numerical simulation and Netlogo virus have similar parameters of infectiousness and recovery rate. Also, both simulations are discrete because they work on time steps (steps for Euler method and ticks for Netlogo). A difference is that Netlogo model is autonomous agent based and factors in the interaction amongst them, while the numerical simulation is an approximate calculation that does not consider individual agents. While the numerical simulation predicted the virus to vanish after 7 weeks (50 days), Netlogo predicted it in 18 weeks. Netlogo virus is more realistic because in the real world because human society is complex and interaction between multiple agents accounts for emergence in human behaviors meanwhile mere equations can barely quantify spread of phenomena in humans. A numeric simulation is deterministic because when given the same input, it will produce similar output while Netlogo is schotastic because the same input won't give similar output and chaotic because a small change in the initial condition produces a large difference in result of virus dynamics.
